the fossil record of the Triassic age (ca. 200 million years ago) (

). The presumed ancestral species of the genus, 

Taxus guyangensis

sp. nov.
, has been dated as far back as the Early Cretaceous (145–100 million years ago) (

). Yews are popular in landscaping and ornamental horticulture, in part because some species (in particular 

T. baccata

) are amenable to trimming as hedges (
Fig. 1B
). The needles are dark-green and aligned into two flat rows on either side of a branch. Most yews are dioecious, with females surrounding seeds with a characteristic fleshy aril (
Fig. 1C
) and males producing small pollen-containing cones (
Fig. 1D
).

The toxicity of yew trees has been known for millennia and began to attract the attention of chemists in the mid-1800s, when the isolation of a powder that was named taxine was reported (

). About 100 years after this discovery 

realized that the preparation was a mixture of metabolites. During the early 1960s, the first structures of taxane diterpenes and pseudoalkaloid diterpenoids (taxines) were elucidated (

; 

). Over the following decades, three taxanes were developed as drugs for the treatment of various 
types
of cancer, namely paclitaxel (approved for medical use as Taxol® in 1993), docetaxel (sold under the brand name Taxotere® since 1995), and cabazitaxel (available under the trade name Jevtana® since 2010) (
Fig. 2A–C
). Taxol became a blockbuster anti-cancer drug, with reported sales exceeding $ 1.5 billion per year in the late 1990s and early 2000s. Taxane drugs are microtubule-stabilizing agents with a unique mode-of-action (

). Microtubules are hollow tubes that 
form part
of the cytoskeleton of eukaryotic cells. They are assembled by the polymerization of α- and β- tubulin, thereby forming dynamic structures that facilitate alternating periods of growth and shortening of cells. Taxane drugs bind primarily to β- tubulin, which promotes the irreversible assembly of microtubules. This suppression of microtubule dynamics leads to the slowing or blocking of mitosis at the metaphase-anaphase transition, and ultimately causes the induction of apoptotic cell death (

).

From a phytochemical perspective, taxanes are a very interesting class of natural products due to the occurrence of an enormous chemical diversity with close to 600 reported structures. Several excellent reviews that cover taxane phytochemistry comprehensively have been published but are now dated (

; 

; 

; 

). Thus, several dozen new taxane chemical entities not covered in previous reviews have been incorporated into the present article, and we discuss the relevance of all known taxanes in the context of the still elusive biosynthetic pathway for the formation of Taxol. We have also made the structural information more easily accessible by integrating structural drawings into tables that list functionalization patterns. We feel that this is a particularly effective approach for consolidating and visualizing the relevant information. Finally, we developed the Yew Genomics Resource (http://langelabtools.wsu.edu/ygr) to provide an overview of the topic for a broader audience and updated the Spektraris online resource (http://langelabtools. wsu.edu/nmr), which now contains more than 500 nuclear magnetic resonance spectral records of taxanes (and over 21,000 records overall).

The term taxane is used for a large and diverse class of metabolites originally isolated from members of the genus 

Taxus

(yews). Taxoids are derivatives of Taxol and are therefore a smaller group within the taxane class, but the term is sometimes used synonymously with ‘taxanes’. Structures of taxanes can be classified as belonging to one of 
eleven types
based on the arrangement of their fused ring systems. Normal 6/8/ 6 taxanes have a linear tricyclic ring system (with the numbers indicating the size of each ring) (
Table 1
). Other tricyclic ring systems are found in 11(15 → 1) 
abeo
taxanes (5/7/6), 11(15 → 1),(10 → 9)di 
abeo
taxanes (5/6/6), and 2(3 → 20)abeotaxanes (6/10/6). Tetracyclic ring systems are characteristic for 3,11-cyclotaxanes (6/5/5/6) and 14,20-cyclotaxanes (6/8/6/6). 3,11:12,20-Dicyclotaxanes (6/5/5/5/6) and 3,11:4,12-dicyclotaxanes (6/5/5/4/6) have pentacyclic skeletons. A hexacyclic ring system is found in 3,11:4,12:14,20-tricyclotaxanes (5/ 5/4/6/6/6). Bicyclic ring systems are representative of 3,8-secotaxanes (6/12) and 11,12-secotaxanes (8/6) (
Table 1
). Cyclotaxane subclasses other than 3,1-cyclotaxanes each have less than a handful of known members, but they do have unique ring systems and are thus listed separately here. In the following paragraphs, we will detail the known chemical diversity for the above-mentioned taxane classes. Consistent with prior reviews on the topic (

; 

; 

; 

), we have adopted a unified nomenclature for taxanes that may differ from the trivial names given in the original papers.

