The initial harvesting of bark from Pacific yew trees for the extraction of Taxol became unsustainable when larger quantities were needed for advanced clinical trials. In 1994, Bristol-Myers Squibb obtained approval for the commercialization of a process that involves the extraction of baccatin III from English yew and subsequent chemical synthesis, which addressed some of the sustainability concerns (reviewed in 

). As an alternative, Phyton Biotech Inc. developed cell suspension cultures of Chinese yew that have been used in commercial-scale fermenters since 2002 to produce Taxol (reviewed in 

). Because of the generally high prices of anti-cancer drugs, demand for Taxol has remained high and researchers are thus continuing to explore other options for its production (

). Engineering Taxol biosynthesis has met tremendous challenges because of the complexity of the pathway (
Fig. 4
), which has been covered in depth in an excellent recent review (

). We will not discuss this topic in detail again here, but thought that an evaluation of taxane chemical diversity, as examined in the present article, in the context of Taxol biosynthesis and engineering would be appreciated by readers.

The diterpene core of Taxol is a 6/8/6- 
type
ring. Appropriate functionalized intermediates of the early steps of Taxol biosynthesis would have the following properties: C-1 non-functionalized or hydroxylated; C-2 non-functionalized, hydroxylated or benzoylated; C-5 non-functionalized, hydroxylated or acetylated (note that this functional group has been hypothesized to migrate to C-4 during later steps of Taxol biosynthesis); C-7 non-functionalized or hydroxylated; C-9 non-functionalized, hydroxylated or further oxidized to a ketone; C-10 non-functionalized, hydroxylated or acetylated; and C-13 non-functionalized or hydroxylated. Surprisingly, only two metabolites in 
Table 2
, which provides an overview of neutral 6/8/6-ring taxanes, combine all of these characteristics: 5α,9α,10β,13α- tetrahydroxytaxa-4 (20),11-diene (

) and 10β- acetoxy-taxa-4(20), 11-diene-2α,5α,7β,9α,13α- pentaol (

). Additional metabolites have been detected in biochemical assays that characterized the functions of genes with roles in early Taxol biosynthesis, including taxa-4(20),11(12)-dien-5α- ol, 5α- acetoxytaxa-4(20),11(12)-diene, taxa-4(20),11(12)-diene-5α,13α- diol, taxa-4(20),11(12)-diene-5α, 10β- diol, 5α- acetoxytaxa-4(20),11(12)-dien-10β- ol, and 5α- acetoxytaxa-4(20),11(12)-diene-10β,13α- diol (

; 

, 2003, 2004; 

; 

). Surprisingly, when these suspected early intermediates of Taxol biosynthesis were used as substrates for 
in vivo
feeding experiments (using 

Taxus

cell suspension cultures or enzyme extracts), they failed to be incorporated into downstream taxanes or taxoids (

). One possible explanation for the apparent lack of appropriate biosynthetic precursors could be that not enough emphasis has been placed thus far on searching for neutral metabolites with a taxa-4(20), 11-diene core. Alternatively, it is possible that enzymes involved in the early functionalization step affecting the taxa-4(20),11-diene core are relatively abundant or catalytically highly competent, and, therefore, the only intermediates that accumulate to appreciable levels are more highly functionalized. Additional genes were shown to encode enzymes capable of functionalizing a 6/8/6-taxane core (e.g., a C-2 hydroxylase, a C-7 hydroxylase, and a C-2 benzoyltransferase) but were only tested with a surrogate substrate and not with a potential Taxol biosynthetic intermediate (

; 

; 

), and their position in the pathway scheme is thus still unknown. Surprisingly, all known taxanes of the 6/8/6- 
type
with a C-4,20-epoxide ring (
Table 6
) have a functionalization pattern that is inconsistent with an involvement in Taxol biosynthesis (acetylation at C-1, C-2, C-7, C-9 or C-13 or ketone functional group at C-13). Among 6/8/6-taxanes with an oxetane ring, 9-dihydrobaccatin III, 10-deacetylbaccatin III and baccatin III would seem to be appropriate intermediates in Taxol biosynthesis (
Table 7
). Genes coding for the enzymes involved in late functionalizations and the assembly of the C-13 side chain of Taxol have been described (

; 

, b, 2004; Sanchez-Mu˜noz et al., 2020; 

). Notably, many of these enzymes have been demonstrated to be highly promiscuous, accepting multiple substrates and generating multiple products (

; 

; 

; 

), which might explain, to a certain extent, the enormous chemical diversity of taxanes observed to occur in the genus 

Taxus

. This fact also illustrates the challenges with engineering a pathway toward the production of a specific product (Taxol). It is likely that mutated versions of enzymes that provide a higher specificity will need to be developed. Taken together, the currently available evidence suggests that critical knowledge gaps exist regarding the order and specificity of functionalization reactions. It will be particularly desirable to identify additional taxanes that might serve as early intermediates of the Taxol biosynthetic pathway.
